<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-186-360  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 186 360.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  Feb 26 1990 v36 n1798 p14(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Congress urged: help loosen export reins. (to Eastern Europe)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Connelly, Joanne.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Several US communications and computer companies have asked USCongress to expand liberalization of the US export controlregulations to Eastern Europe in light of changes in the area'spolitical environment.andP;  Executives from Honeywell, DEC and theComputer and Communications Industry Association told a HouseForeign Affairs subcommittee that the US government was not doingenough to loosen restrictions.andP;  Less than one week earlier, in Feb1990, Western European nations rejected a US proposal to lift manyrestrictions, while maintaining tighter controls on exports to theUSSR and some Warsaw Pact countries.andP;  The US Department of Defenseis probably the most outspoken of the US companies' opposition; aDOD official told the House Subcommittee on International EconomicPolicy and trade that the USSR is a continuing military threat,and the US should take a measured approach to relaxation ofcontrols.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Eastern EuropeCommerceRestraint of TradeUnited States. Congress.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>